ACT IV. Scssm: II.

In this scene Pamphilus is introduced in conversation with his mother. She had been told by Laches of the declarations he had made in her favour, and, resolved not t'o yield to him in point of generosity, proposes to retire into the country, and leave him at liberty to take home his wife. This offer, which she thought would be well received, is altogether inconsistent with his views, as it deprives him of a pretence for separating from Philumena; and, therefore, he eamestly urges her not to think of it.
